aa(lp124
VThe second issue:
p125
aVYour country could be under cyberattack
p126
aVwith entire regions plunged into total darkness,
p127
aVand you may not even know
p128
aVwho's attacking you.
p129
aVCyber weapons have this peculiar feature:
p130
aVthey can be used
p131
aVwithout leaving traces.
p132
aVThis gives a tremendous advantage to the attacker,
p133
aVbecause the defender
p134
aVdoesn't know who to fight back against.
p135
aVAnd if the defender retaliates against the wrong adversary,
p136
aVthey risk making one more enemy
p137
aVand ending up diplomatically isolated.
p138
aVThis issue isn't just theoretical.
p139
aa(lp140
VIn May 2007, Estonia was the victim of cyberattacks,
p141
aVthat damaged its communication
p142
aVand banking systems.
p143
aVEstonia accused Russia.
p144
aVBut NATO, though it defends Estonia,
p145
aVreacted very prudently. Why?
p146
aVBecause NATO couldn't be 100% sure
p147
aVthat the Kremlin was indeed behind these attacks.
p148
aVSo to sum up, on the one hand,
p149
aVwhen a possible enemy announces
p150
aVthey're building a cyberwar unit,
p151
aVyou don't know whether it's for attack
p152
aVor defense.
p153
aVOn the other hand,
p154
aVwe know that these weapons give an advantage to attacking.
p155
aa(lp156
VIn a major article published in 1978,
p157
aVProfessor Robert Jervis of Columbia University in New York
p158
aVdescribed a model to understand
p159
aVhow conflicts could arise.
p160
aVIn this context,
p161
aVwhen you don't know if the potential enemy
p162
aVis preparing for defense or attack,
p163
aVand if the weapons give an advantage to attacking,
p164
aVthen this environment is
p165
aVmost likely to spark a conflict.
